3 important things I've learned from managing a team of 108:

How to hire. When I started I just hired friends and people that I thought were cool (I was 22!) and I put very little emphasis on skills or real fit with the company mission. It was a mess.  When I learned how to hire well, I focused on a holistic view of who they are, what they’re dreams are, their skills (soft skills and technical skills), and their passion for the work we do

When to let someone go. This was a lesson I’ve had to learn the hard way more than once, but one thing is clear: when you know it isn’t a right fit, don’t wait. Your vision and dream depend on your loyalty to the growth and evolution of the business as a whole. 

How to be an intentional and conscious leader that really cares. When I started I was so sensitive to every piece of feedback - when an employee was unhappy I’d spiral into despair. When I learned to really listen things changed - we started to have great ideas being brought forward from everyone on the team - which is what has made the company incredible.

I started @thedragontree when I was 23 with a big dream, a shoestring budget, and a business partner. 

One of those things was a huge asset to me, one was an overcomeable challenge, and one made me cry every day.

I’ve always loved collaboration, to be able to work with people to create something feels like magic to me, and so I thought it was going to be THE BEST to have a business partner in my dream to open a spa - so I asked my co-worker to start a business with me. 

By the time we opened the doors to the spa - we weren’t talking.

We didn’t see eye to eye about how to manage finances, how we wanted to grow the spa, how much we wanted to work, and she wouldn’t sit down and talk to me in order to sort out the details of who will be doing what. It was a mess.

As time went on it became untenable. 
I felt a tight, heavy feeling in my being every time I knew I was going to see her.
Our business was suffering.

I knew something had to change.

Let me take you into what I shifted energetically . . .

I leaned into the soul of the business to see what it needed and to see if I could align myself with that.
I brought all of my energy back into myself, rather than trying to control my business partner and the outcome.
I severed all energetic cords that were no longer healthy with my business partner.

And how this transmitted to the physical plane was that my boundaries were clear af, my communication was no longer stifled, and almost immediately she came to the table with an offer for me to buy her 1/2 of the business, which I was delighted to do!

This is why I love to alchemize energetics and business - it allows new outcomes to arise.

And once the tense energy was cleared out of the space - the spa took off . . . quickly. It was so incredible to see how much shifted once the vibrations of the space aligned with our mission!!

When people ask me what I do I never know what to lead with . . . 

It’s kind of weird running two companies that are so different, and yet weave together from time to time.  

I started The Dragontree in 2003 as a spa where I did the majority of the treatments, worked the front desk, and was head toilet cleaner - and it’s grown into a multi-million dollar wellness brand that manufactures incredible products, self-publishes and sells tens of thousands of books and planners every year, and trains people in how to get their dreams and also how to be a soulful life coach (oh and we still have our spas of course ;))

Now my position at The Dragontree is CEO and visionary - and my team there does an incredible job of taking care of our clients and running things day to day. ((thank you!!)) And every once in a while there are things that only I can handle, and so I step in and do my best. 

Around 2017 I really felt the deep call to be back with clients again one on one - and so I started a very side thing of doing energy work with individuals and in groups. It was this fun thing that I loved to do and it didn’t dominate my work life as I was still in development of many facets of The Dragontree.

Then in 2020 when Covid shut everything down I decided to go alllll the way in on creating my personal online business. I started to run more high touch groups, opened the doors to more one on one clients (and filled up immediately), and devoted myself to the art of this work even further.

Now I get to mix my love and experience of business with the deep internal work and energy alchemy to support my one on one clients and also for my Mastermind. It’s so full, and I love it. 

So when people ask me what I do - I don’t know whether to say I have a wellness brand, or I’m a spiritual guide and energy alchemist, or that I’m a soulful business mentor for leaders . . . so usually I just say “I work to create peace” because it’s what the common thread is for everything.

5 things to let go of as we enter the Winter Solstice Portal:
1. Defensiveness: Can you lower the protective wall around your heart?
What would it be like if you allowed yourself to soften and allow. So often we’ve protected our hearts in order to avoid feeling pain - but in the end we still have the pain and then additionally have closed hearts that constrict the flow of love through us.
2. Judgements: Can you release the need to categorize things into good and bad? We’ve been trained our whole lives that our value comes from being able to
critically evaluate things (including ourselves and others) and be on the “right” side. It’s led to lifetimes of judgment and constriction. What would it be like to release yourself from the job of judger?
3. Ego: Can you approach yourself with lighthearted curiosity?
The looser you can be with the grip of the ego on your life the more you’ll be able
to explore the depths of your being and the expansive terrain you can navigate.
4. The need to fix: Can you accept yourself with love just as you are?
What if there was nothing wrong with you? What if there was nothing to fix? The
ease that arises when we no longer hold ourselves as broken comes with incredible growth and evolution (strange right?)
5. An activated nervous system: Can you soothe your body with calming breaths and deep care?
A regulated nervous system is the best gift we can give ourselves - but it takes our deliberate care to shift from an overactivated nervous system to one that is stable and supportive to our dreams - but you can do it!

Today I want to share with you how the Solstice came to be a huge part of my life.

I was raised in a family that wasn’t super religious - my parents wanted us to explore for ourselves what we believed, we celebrated Christmas but in a pretty secular way. As an adult (ok - adult-ish), I got married to my beloved Peter who was raised Jewish, celebrated Hanukkah, but wasn’t super connected to those traditions. 

As we were embarking on creating our own family, we wanted to celebrate something that held deep meaning to both of us - and the Winter Solstice was the perfect way for us to honor the true felt experience of the season and  connect and celebrate together. 

When we had kids, we wanted to incorporate fun ways to celebrate the Solstice, so one of my favorite traditions we’ve created is hiding little battery operated candles throughout the house and turning out all the lights.  Our kids would then go on a hunt to find the light . . . in the dark. 

It focuses our awareness on what’s here for us in this season: an invitation to explore how in the darkest times can we look for, remember, and know the light.

Forgiveness can be a heavy subject, but if you’re looking to become a liberated human on this planet - it’s essential and there are 6 tenants that I’ve found help guide the forgiveness process. 
1) Recognize the inner child in everyone. People are still looking to get their needs met, they're still seeking approval and validation. We are all trying our best to make things work with the tools that we have. 

In this process we often cause pain for others and others cause pain for us. 

If you’ve been on the receiving end of pain, there’s a good chance that the person was acting out of confusion. They may not have truly understood the impact of their actions. 

The behavior still may not be okay but understanding this helps forgiveness feel like an option.

2) Find Equiminity. We are all one. Remember this even in moments of struggle and anger. Find a place within, where we are connected, where we are the same.

This helps move us out of the “why me mindset” and it leads us to understand what pain may have led them down this path.

This takes a lot of bravery to switch from anger to curiosity. But bravery is what sets us free.

3) Consider that a life long punishment may not be reasonable.

Consider that any resentment that lasts a lifetime may be cruel and unusual punishment.

Especially when we take this stance against ourselves for a mistake. 

4) Have your experience. Feel the pain and anger.

One of the flames of awareness I’ve been working for decades now but really intensely recently is forgiveness. It’s one of the most challenging and freeing practices that I find myself consistently engaged in. 

Forgiveness is pivotal for your liberation on this Earth. Here are six guiding tenants that help navigate this transformative practice:

1) Recognize the Inner Child: Understand that beneath the surface, every person has their inner child seeking approval and validation. 

We’re all navigating life with the tools we have, often causing and experiencing pain in the process. 

Recognize that some may act out of confusion, not fully comprehending the impact of their actions. While their behavior might not be excused, this awareness makes forgiveness an option.

2) Embrace Oneness: In moments of turmoil and anger, remember our interconnectedness. Seek the common thread that unites us, moving away from the “why me” mindset. 

This shift allows you to fathom the pain that may have led them astray. It takes courage to pivot from anger to curiosity, but it’s this bravery that sets you free.

3) Reconsider Prolonged Punishment: Reflect on whether lifelong resentment is justifiable. Is it not a form of excessive, cruel punishment, especially when we direct it at ourselves for past mistakes?

4) Embrace Your Experience: Allow your feelings to surface. Don’t suppress them, as bottling up emotions only leads to inner turmoil. 

To embark on the path of forgiveness, you must fully accept and allow your experience to flow through you.

5) A Gift to Yourself: Understand that forgiveness is a gift to yourself. By withholding it, you burden yourself with the role of a self-appointed punisher, creating a mental prison. This prison, however, only holds you captive. Cease being the warden to a ghostly prisoner.

6) An Ongoing Commitment: Consider forgiveness not as a single act but as an enduring commitment. It’s a process that unfolds over time, nurturing your own growth and healing. 🌟💕

I love Carol Dweck’s ideas on growth mindset and fixed mindset. It’s been foundational in the way I’ve learned to parent and also how I’ve learned to hold my own capacity for change.

In Carols’ studies she found that some people see themselves in a relatively unchanging way – I’m bad at sports, good at math, unpopular, a decent speller, etc. She calls this a “fixed mindset.” 

Other people tend to see themselves as capable of changing these qualities by working at them. She calls this a “growth mindset.” 

You might think that a fixed mindset wouldn’t be a problem if we see ourselves as good, talented, smart, and attractive. But it can still work against us, because this makes us avoid situations that might challenge or disprove these beliefs. It keeps us from getting to know ourselves more deeply. Because if we don’t like what we discover (“Oh no! I’m not that talented and also I’m getting old!”) – and we see ourselves in a fixed way – then we’re fucked!

The good news is that everyone can develop a growth mindset. Even though it means getting real *real* with ourselves about our weaknesses, as we start to work toward change and we see we’re much more malleable than we thought, this makes us RESILIENT.
